From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0027/N] oopStorage: use plain volatile load for active_index_safe under CHERI

`OopStorage::Block::active_index_safe` reads an 8-byte `size_t`
field atomically via `SafeFetchN((intptr_t*)&_active_index, 0)`.
The accompanying `STATIC_ASSERT(sizeof(intptr_t) == sizeof(size_t))`
holds on every 64-bit platform except CHERI/Morello purecap, where
`intptr_t` is `__intcap` (16 bytes). Beyond the assert, `SafeFetchN`'s
16-byte read would walk past the 8-byte `_active_index`.

HotSpot only provides `SafeFetch32` and `SafeFetchN`; there is no
`SafeFetch64`. Under CHERI use a plain volatile load — the "safe"
property of SafeFetchN (returning errValue on SIGSEGV) is a
defensive measure for the rare case the caller passes a stale
Block*; the only current caller paths are debug/diagnostic and
won't have a stale pointer in practice.

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md §6 (patch 0027)

--- a/src/hotspot/share/gc/shared/oopStorage.cpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/share/gc/shared/oopStorage.cpp
@@ -299,8 +299,18 @@ void OopStorage::Block::set_active_index(size_t index) {
 }

 size_t OopStorage::Block::active_index_safe(const Block* block) {
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+  // CHERI: SafeFetchN takes intptr_t* and would read sizeof(intptr_t)==16
+  // bytes, over-reading the 8-byte size_t field. There is no SafeFetch64
+  // helper in HotSpot, so use a plain volatile load here. active_index_safe
+  // is a defensive read; the caller (only oopStorage debug paths) does not
+  // require the SIGSEGV-trapping property that SafeFetchN provides.
+  STATIC_ASSERT(sizeof(int64_t) == sizeof(block->_active_index));
+  return *reinterpret_cast<const volatile size_t*>(&block->_active_index);
+#else
   STATIC_ASSERT(sizeof(intptr_t) == sizeof(block->_active_index));
   return SafeFetchN((intptr_t*)&block->_active_index, 0);
+#endif
 }

 unsigned OopStorage::Block::get_index(const oop* ptr) const {
